	<!-- Write the section content inside a paragraph 
        element, You can also include images with <img> tag -->
        <div id="lab-article-section-2-content" class="content">
	<p><strong>
	Study the color change of an <font color="blue">indicator </font> in different <font color="blue">pH </font> solutions.
	 <br><br>
	<img  src="images/phscalelab.JPG" width="460" height="340" />
	</strong></p>
	</div>
	
      </section>


	 <!-- Second section of the article-->
      <section id="lab-article-section-3">
        
        <div id="lab-article-section-3-icon" class="icon">
          <!-- Enclose the icon image for the section. -->
	  <img src="../images/theory.jpg" />
	</div>


        <!-- The heading for the section can be enclosed in a 
        div tag and shown with a <h2> tag -->
	<div id="lab-article-section-3-heading" class="heading">
	 Theory
	</div>
				
	<!-- Write the section content inside a paragraph 
        element, You can also include images with <img> tag -->
        <div id="lab-article-section-3-content" class="content">
	<strong>
	
	<p>
	Acid-base indicators are frequently weak acids or bases. The basic principle is given as follows<br><br>
	<div align="center"><img src="images/formula9.jpeg"></img></div><br><br><br>	
	</p>
	<p>
	Here HInd stands for the acid form and Ind<sup>-</sup> for the conjugate base of the indicator. It is the ratio of these that determines the color of the solution and that connects the color to the pH value. Here the equation is derived from the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acidity_constant" target="_blank">acidity constant</a> of the indicator.
	</p>
  	</strong>
	</div>
	</section>
	
